values.description:
While reviewing this tutorial, I noticed there's almost no documentation on the arguments which `gz log --filter` accepts. So I dug a bit through the source code and added a few guidelines. 

I also ran into a few other issues which I ticketed at the Gazebo repo:

* [Log filtering doesn't handle nested models](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/gazebo/issues/2157/log-filtering-doesnt-handle-nested-models)

* [gz log filter joints test has wrong expectations](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/gazebo/issues/2158/gz-log-filter-joints-test-has-wrong)
values.title: Add more explanation to the kinds of filters gz log accepts

summary.raw:
While reviewing this tutorial, I noticed there's almost no documentation on the arguments which `gz log --filter` accepts. So I dug a bit through the source code and added a few guidelines. 

I also ran into a few other issues which I ticketed at the Gazebo repo:

* [Log filtering doesn't handle nested models](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/gazebo/issues/2157/log-filtering-doesnt-handle-nested-models)

* [gz log filter joints test has wrong expectations](https://bitbucket.org/osrf/gazebo/issues/2158/gz-log-filter-joints-test-has-wrong)
summary.html:
While reviewing this tutorial, I noticed there's almost no documentation on the arguments which gz log --filter accepts. So I dug a bit through the source code and added a few guidelines.

I also ran into a few other issues which I ticketed at the Gazebo repo:

  • Log filtering doesn't handle nested models

  • gz log filter joints test has wrong expectations

values.description:
This tutorial describes how to set the velocity or joint using three methods.

* The first is an instantaneous method that does not apply forces or torques.
* The second is a perfect velocity controller that only works using ODE
* The third is by applying forces using PID controllers.
values.title: Set velocity tutorial

summary.raw:

* The third is by applying forces using PID controllers.
summary.html:
This tutorial describes how to set the velocity or joint using three methods.

  • The third is by applying forces using PID controllers.

values.description:
We're currently requiring to install `libgdal1h` in the [DEM tutorial](http://gazebosim.org/tutorials/?tut=dem). This package doesn't exist in all Ubuntu distributions. It's better to remove it, `libgdal-dev` will pull the dependencies needed.

See [this Gazebo question](http://answers.gazebosim.org/question/16769/i-tried-installing-dem-digital-elevation-models-support-for-gazebo-as-described-in-httpgazebosimorgtutorialstutdem/) for some extra info.
values.title: Remove libgdal1h dependency

summary.raw:

See [this Gazebo question](http://answers.gazebosim.org/question/16769/i-tried-installing-dem-digital-elevation-models-support-for-gazebo-as-described-in-httpgazebosimorgtutorialstutdem/) for some extra info.

values.description:
The optional DART package that works with the Gazebo default branch has changed from `libdart-core5-dev` to `libdart6-dev`. This PR updates the documentation in the [ install_from_source](http://gazebosim.org/tutorials?tut=install_from_source) tutorial.

The [gravity_compensation](http://gazebosim.org/tutorials?tut=gravity_compensation) tutorial (pull request #436) depends on DART. This PR updates the tutorial prerequisites to reflect this.
